On Wednesday, February 16, 2005, at 02:10PM, MonkeyBoy <chris.gause(-at-)gmail.com> wrote:

>Ok, my starter is turning too SLOW to start. I'm about to pop in a new
>battery and new cables. Somewhere I read that the ground strap on the
>Tranny may be loose.

It's a braided cable and it rusts out over time like the original battery negative cable.

>I'm wondering if it would be advantagous to get a
>negitive battery cable with two leads. One lead to the chasis where
>it's at by factory default, and one line to the engine/tranny for
>direct ground to the battery.

The path the current takes during starting is:

battery pos -> starter -> transmission case -> tranny strap -> body -> battery neg

The current is only going to take one path (the one of least resistance) but both cables are going to rust out...

